# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jmeter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jmeter/apache-jmeter] JMeter can be used as a unit-test tool for JDBC database connections, FTP, LDAP, web services, JMS, HTTP, generic TCP connections and OS-native processes.
[src:jmeter/apache-jmeter] One can also configure JMeter as a monitor, although this is typically used as a basic monitoring solution rather than advanced monitoring.
[src:jmeter/apache-jmeter] It can be used for some functional testing as well.
[src:jmeter/apache-jmeter] JMeter supports variable parameterization, assertions (response validation), per-thread cookies, configuration variables and a variety of reports.
[src:jmeter/apache-jmeter] JMeter architecture is based on plugins.
[src:jmeter/apache-jmeter] JMeter Plugins is an independent project for Apache JMeter.
[src:jmeter/apache-jmeter] Each plugin serves a different purpose while expediting the process of creating and executing JMeter Test Plan.
[src:jmeter/apache-jmeter] Users can install plugins via the Plugin Manager.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] In this section, you will learn how to create a basic Test Plan to test a Web site.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] You will create five users that send requests to two pages on the JMeter Web site.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Also, you will tell the users to run their tests twice.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] So, the total number of requests is (5 users) x (2 requests) x (repeat 2 times) = 20 HTTP requests.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] To construct the Test Plan, you will use the following elements: Thread Group, HTTP Request, HTTP Request Defaults, and Graph Results.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] For a more advanced Test Plan, see Building an Advanced Web Test Plan.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] The first step you want to do with every JMeter Test Plan is to add a Thread Group element.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] The Thread Group tells JMeter the number of users you want to simulate, how often the users should send requests, and how many requests they should send.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Go ahead and add the ThreadGroup element by first selecting the Test Plan, clicking your right mouse button to get the Add menu, and then select Add → ThreadGroup.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] You should now see the Thread Group element under Test Plan.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] If you do not see the element, then "expand" the Test Plan tree by clicking on the Test Plan element.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Next, you need to modify the default properties.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Select the Thread Group element in the tree, if you have not already selected it.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Start by providing a more descriptive name for our Thread Group.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Next, increase the number of users (called threads) to 5.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] In the next field, the Ramp-Up Period, leave the default value of 1 seconds.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] This property tells JMeter how long to delay between starting each user.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] For example, if you enter a Ramp-Up Period of 5 seconds, JMeter will finish starting all of your users by the end of the 5 seconds.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] So, if we have 5 users and a 5 second Ramp-Up Period, then the delay between starting users would be 1 second (5 users / 5 seconds = 1 user per second).
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] If you set the value to 0, then JMeter will immediately start all of your users.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Finally enter a value of 2 in the Loop Count field.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] This property tells JMeter how many times to repeat your test.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] If you enter a loop count value of 1, then JMeter will run your test only once.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] To have JMeter repeatedly run your Test Plan, select the Forever checkbox.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] In most applications, you have to manually accept changes you make in a Control Panel.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] However, in JMeter, the Control Panel automatically accepts your changes as you make them.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] If you change the name of an element, the tree will be updated with the new text after you leave the Control Panel (for example, when selecting another tree element).
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] See Figure 4.2 for the completed JMeter Users Thread Group.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Now that we have defined our users, it is time to define the tasks that they will be performing.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] In this section, you will specify the default settings for your HTTP requests.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] And then, in section 4.3, you will add HTTP Request elements which use some of the default settings you specified here.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Begin by selecting the JMeter Users (Thread Group) element.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Click your right mouse button to get the Add menu, and then select Add → Config Element → HTTP Request Defaults.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Then select this new element to view its Control Panel (see Figure 4.3).
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Like most JMeter elements, the HTTP Request Defaults Control Panel has a name field that you can modify.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] In this example, leave this field with the default value.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Skip to the next field, which is the Web Server's Server Name/IP.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] For the Test Plan that you are building, all HTTP requests will be sent to the same Web server, jmeter.apache.org.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] This is the only field that we will specify a default, so leave the remaining fields with their default values.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] The HTTP Request Defaults element does not tell JMeter to send an HTTP request.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] It simply defines the default values that the HTTP Request elements use.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Nearly all web testing should use cookie support, unless your application specifically doesn't use cookies.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] To add cookie support, simply add an HTTP Cookie Manager to each Thread Group in your test plan.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] This will ensure that each thread gets its own cookies, but shared across all HTTP Request objects.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] To add the HTTP Cookie Manager, simply select the Thread Group, and choose Add → Config Element → HTTP Cookie Manager, either from the Edit Menu, or from the right-click pop-up menu.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] In our Test Plan, we need to make two HTTP requests.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] The first one is for the JMeter home page (http://jmeter.apache.org/), and the second one is for the Changes page (http://jmeter.apache.org/changes.html).
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] JMeter sends requests in the order that they appear in the tree.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Start by adding the first HTTP Request to the JMeter Users element (Add → Sampler → HTTP Request).
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Then, select the HTTP Request element in the tree and edit the following properties (see Figure 4.6): Change the Name field to "Home Page".
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Remember that you do not have to set the Server Name field because you already specified this value in the HTTP Request Defaults element.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Next, add the second HTTP Request and edit the following properties (see Figure 4.7: Change the Name field to "Changes".
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] The final element you need to add to your Test Plan is a Listener.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] This element is responsible for storing all of the results of your HTTP requests in a file and presenting a visual model of the data.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Select the JMeter Users element and add a Graph Results listener (Add → Listener → Backend Listener).
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] It's not the case here, but some web-sites require you to login before permitting you to perform certain actions.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] In a web-browser, the login will be shown as a form for the user name and password, and a button to submit the form.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] The button generates a POST request, passing the values of the form items as parameters.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] To do this in JMeter, add an HTTP Request, and set the method to POST.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] You'll need to know the names of the fields used by the form, and the target page.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] These can be found out by inspecting the code of the login page. [If this is difficult to do, you can use the JMeter Proxy Recorder to record the login sequence.] Set the path to the target of the submit button.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Click the Add button twice and enter the username and password details.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] Sometimes the login form contains additional hidden fields.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] When creating a Test Plan, on each Thread Group iteration, we can choose to simulate the same user running multiple iterations, or different users running one iteration.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] You can configure this behaviour on Thread Group element, and have HTTP Cache Manager, HTTP Cookie Manager, HTTP Authorization Manager controlled by this setting.
[src:jmeter/build-web-test-plan] You can choose to clear the cookies/cache content/authorization in the CookieManager/CacheManager/Authorization Manager, or choose to be controlled by the Thread Group.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] Several test elements use JMeter properties to control their behaviour.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] These properties are normally resolved when the class is loaded.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] Samplers perform the actual work of JMeter.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] Each sampler (except Flow Control Action) generates one or more sample results.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] The sample results have various attributes (success/fail, elapsed time, data size etc.) and can be viewed in the various listeners.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] This controller lets you send an FTP "retrieve file" or "upload file" request to an FTP server.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] Configuration Element so you do not have to enter the same information for each FTP Request Generative Controller.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] When downloading a file, it can be stored on disk (Local File) or in the Response Data, or both.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] Latency is set to the time it takes to login.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] Descriptive name for this sampler that is shown in the tree.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] Domain name or IP address of the FTP server.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] , then this specific port is used, otherwise JMeter uses the default FTP port.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] File to retrieve or name of destination file to upload.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] File to upload, or destination for downloads (defaults to remote file name).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] Provides the contents for the upload, overrides the Local File property.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] Whether to store contents of retrieved file in response data.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] This sampler lets you send an HTTP/HTTPS request to a web server.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] It also lets you control whether or not JMeter parses HTML files for images and other embedded resources and sends HTTP requests to retrieve them.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] The default parser is org.apache.jmeter.protocol.http.parser.LagartoBasedHtmlParser.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] This can be changed by using the property "htmlparser.className" - see jmeter.properties for details.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] If you are going to send multiple requests to the same web server, consider using an HTTP Request Defaults Configuration Element so you do not have to enter the same information for each HTTP Request.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] Or, instead of manually adding HTTP Requests, you may want to use JMeter's HTTP(S) Test Script Recorder to create them.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] This can save you time if you have a lot of HTTP requests or requests with many parameters.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] uses the Tomcat mod_jk protocol (allows testing of Tomcat in AJP mode without needing Apache httpd) The AJP Sampler does not support multiple file upload; only the first file will be used.
