[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] If the request requires server or proxy login authorization (i.e. where a browser would create a pop-up dialog box), you will also have to add an HTTP Authorization Manager Configuration Element.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] For normal logins (i.e. where the user enters login information in a form), you will need to work out what the form submit button does, and create an HTTP request with the appropriate method (usually POST) and the appropriate parameters from the form definition.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] If the page uses HTTP, you can use the JMeter Proxy to capture the login sequence.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] A separate SSL context is used for each thread.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] By default, since version 5.0, the SSL context is retained during a Thread Group iteration and reset for each test iteration.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p01] If in your test plan the same user iterates multiple times, then you should set this to false.
