[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] This Sampler can send all 8 different LDAP requests to an LDAP server.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] It is an extended version of the LDAP sampler, therefore it is harder to configure, but can be made much closer resembling a real LDAP session.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] If you are going to send multiple requests to the same LDAP server, consider using an LDAP Extended Request Defaults Configuration Element so you do not have to enter the same information for each LDAP Request.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] Any LDAP request is part of an LDAP session, so the first thing that should be done is starting a session to the LDAP server.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] For starting this session a thread bind is used, which is equal to the LDAP "bind" operation.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] The user is requested to give a username (Distinguished name) and password, which will be used to initiate a session.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] When no password, or the wrong password is specified, an anonymous session is started.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] Take care, omitting the password will not fail this test, a wrong password will.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] The name (or IP-address) of the LDAP server.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] The port number that the LDAP server is listening to.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] If this is omitted JMeter assumes the LDAP server is listening on the default port(389).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] The distinguished name of the base object that will be used for any subsequent operation.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] It can be used as a starting point for all operations.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] You cannot start any operation on a higher level than this DN!
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] Full distinguished name of the user as which you want to bind.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] If omitted it will result in an anonymous bind.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] If it is incorrect, the sampler will return an error and revert to an anonymous bind.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] This is simply the operation to end a session.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] It is equal to the LDAP "unbind" operation.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] This is a combination of the LDAP "bind" and "unbind" operations.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] It can be used for an authentication request/password check for any user.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] It will open a new session, just to check the validity of the user/password combination, and end the session again.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] If it is incorrect, the sampler will return an error.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] It can be used to rename an entry, but also for moving an entry or a complete subtree to a different place in the LDAP tree.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] The current distinguished name of the object you want to rename or move, relative to the given DN in the thread bind operation.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] The new distinguished name of the object you want to rename or move, relative to the given DN in the thread bind operation.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] It can be used to add any kind of object to the LDAP server.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] Distinguished name of the object you want to add, relative to the given DN in the thread bind operation.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] A list of attributes and their values you want to use for the object.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] If you need to add a multiple value attribute, you need to add the same attribute with their respective values several times to the list.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] Distinguished name of the object you want to delete, relative to the given DN in the thread bind operation.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] This is the LDAP "search" operation, and will be used for defining searches.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] Distinguished name of the subtree you want your search to look in, relative to the given DN in the thread bind operation.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] searchfilter, must be specified in LDAP syntax.
