[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] AccessLogSampler was designed to read access logs and generate http requests.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] For those not familiar with the access log, it is the log the webserver maintains of every request it accepted.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] Tomcat uses the common format for access logs.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] This means any webserver that uses the common log format can use the AccessLogSampler.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] Server that use common log format include: Tomcat, Resin, Weblogic, and SunOne.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] Everything else is stripped out and ignored.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] For example, the response code is completely ignored by the parser.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] For the future, it might be nice to filter out entries that do not have a response code of 200.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] Extending the sampler should be fairly simple.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] The current implementation of AccessLogSampler uses the generator to create a new HTTPSampler.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] The servername, port and get images are set by AccessLogSampler.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] Next, the parser is called with integer 1, telling it to parse one entry.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] After that, HTTPSampler.sample() is called to make the request.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] Classes implementing Generator interface should provide concrete implementation for all the methods.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] For an example of how to implement either interface, refer to StandardGenerator and TCLogParser.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] Domain name or IP address of the web server.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] The log parser class is responsible for parsing the logs.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] The filter class is used to filter out certain lines.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] The TCLogParser processes the access log independently for each thread.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] The SharedTCLogParser and OrderPreservingLogParser share access to the file, i.e. each thread gets the next entry in the log.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] The SessionFilter is intended to handle Cookies across threads.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] It does not filter out any entries, but modifies the cookie manager so that the cookies for a given IP are processed by a single thread at a time.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] If two threads try to process samples from the same client IP address, then one will be forced to wait until the other has completed.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] The LogFilter is intended to allow access log entries to be filtered by filename and regex, as well as allowing for the replacement of file extensions.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p02] However, it is not currently possible to configure this via the GUI, so it cannot really be used.
