[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If selected, only the message headers will be retrieved.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If so, then the entire raw message is stored in the Response Data; the headers are not stored as they are available in the data.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If not, the message headers are stored as Response Headers.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Indicates that the connection to the server does not use any security protocol.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Indicates that the connection to the server must use the SSL protocol.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Indicates that the connection to the server should attempt to start the TLS protocol.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If the server does not start the TLS protocol the connection will be terminated.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] When selected it will accept all certificates independent of the CA.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] When selected it will only accept certificates that are locally trusted.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Path to file containing the trusted certificates.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Relative paths are resolved against the current directory.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Failing that, against the directory containing the test script (JMX file).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Messages are stored as subsamples of the main sampler.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Multipart message parts are stored as subsamples of the message.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Flow Control Action sampler is a sampler that is intended for use in a conditional controller.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Rather than generate a sample, the test element either pauses or stops the selected target.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] This sampler can also be useful in conjunction with the Transaction Controller, as it allows pauses to be included without needing to generate a sample.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] For variable delays, set the pause time to zero, and add a Timer as a child.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The "Stop" action stops the thread or test after completing any samples that are in progress.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The "Stop Now" action stops the test without waiting for samples to complete; it will interrupt any active samples.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If some threads fail to stop within the 5 second time-limit, a message will be displayed in GUI mode.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] You can try using the Stop command to see if this will stop the threads, but if not, you should exit JMeter.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] In CLI mode, JMeter will exit if some threads fail to stop within the 5 second time limit.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The time to wait can be changed using the JMeter property jmeterengine.threadstop.wait.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The SMTP Sampler can send mail messages using SMTP/SMTPS protocol.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] It is possible to set security protocols for the connection (SSL and TLS), as well as user authentication.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If a security protocol is used a verification on the server certificate will occur.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] With this option the certificate chain will be validated against the local truststore file.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Port to be used to connect to the server.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Connection timeout value in milliseconds (socket level).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Read timeout value in milliseconds (socket level).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Indicates that the connection to the SMTP server does not use any security protocol.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Indicates that the connection to the SMTP server must use the SSL protocol.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Indicates that the connection to the SMTP server should attempt to start the TLS protocol.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] " header is omitted from the mail that is sent.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] " header, though some e-mail clients may display it identically.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Additional headers can be defined using this button.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If the message body is empty and there is a single file, then send the file contents as the message body.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Calculates the message size and stores it in the sample result.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The OS Process Sampler is a sampler that can be used to execute commands on the local machine.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] It should allow execution of any command that can be run from the command line.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Validation of the return code can be enabled, and the expected return code can be specified.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Note that OS shells generally provide command-line parsing.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] This varies between OSes, but generally the shell will split parameters on white-space.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Some shells expand wild-card file names; some don't.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The quoting mechanism also varies between OSes.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The sampler deliberately does not do any parsing or quote handling.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The command and its parameters must be provided in the form expected by the executable.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] This means that the sampler settings will not be portable between OSes.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Many OSes have some built-in commands which are not provided as separate executables.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] For example the Windows DIR command is part of the command interpreter (CMD.EXE).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] These built-ins cannot be run as independent programs, but have to be provided as arguments to the appropriate command interpreter.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Key/Value pairs added to environment when running command.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If omitted, output is captured and returned as the response data.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Note 500 is used as an error indicator in JMeter so you should not use it.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If the timeout expires before the command finishes, JMeter will attempt to kill the OS process.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] This sampler lets you send a Request to a MongoDB.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Name of the JMeter variable that the MongoDB connection is bound to.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] This sampler allows you to run Cypher queries through the Bolt protocol.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Every request uses a connection acquired from the pool and returns it to the pool when the sampler completes.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The connection pool size defaults to 100 and is configurable.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The measured response time corresponds to the "full" query execution, including both the time to execute the cypher query AND the time to consume the results sent back by the database.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Whether to add or not query result data to the sampler response (default false).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Note that activating this has a memory overhead, use it wisely.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Whether to access the database in WRITE or READ mode.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Use WRITE for a standalone Neo4j instance.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] For a Neo4j cluster, select mode depending on whether the query writes to the database.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] That setting will allow correct routing to the cluster leader, followers or read replicas.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Required for Neo4j 4.0+, unless querying the default database.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] It is strongly advised to use query parameters, allowing the database to cache and reuse execution plans.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Logic Controllers determine the order in which Samplers are processed.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Simple Logic Controller lets you organize your Samplers and other Logic Controllers.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Unlike other Logic Controllers, this controller provides no functionality beyond that of a storage device.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Descriptive name for this controller that is shown in the tree.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] In this example, we created a Test Plan that sends two Ant HTTP requests and two Log4J HTTP requests.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] We grouped the Ant and Log4J requests by placing them inside Simple Logic Controllers.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Remember, the Simple Logic Controller has no effect on how JMeter processes the controller(s) you add to it.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] So, in this example, JMeter sends the requests in the following order: Ant Home Page, Ant News Page, Log4J Home Page, Log4J History Page.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Note, the File Reporter is configured to store the results in a file named "simple-test.dat" in the current directory.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If you add Generative or Logic Controllers to a Loop Controller, JMeter will loop through them a certain number of times, in addition to the loop value you specified for the Thread Group.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] For example, if you add one HTTP Request to a Loop Controller with a loop count of two, and configure the Thread Group loop count to three, JMeter will send a total of 2 * 3 = 6 HTTP Requests.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] JMeter will expose the looping index as a variable named __jm__<Name of your element>__idx.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] So for example, if your Loop Controller is named LC, then you can access the looping index through ${__jm__LC__idx}.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The number of times the subelements of this controller will be iterated each time through a test run.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The value -1 is equivalent to checking the Forever toggle.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] When using a function in this field, be aware it may be evaluated multiple times.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] will evaluate it to a different value for each child samplers of Loop Controller and result into unwanted behaviour.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] In this example, we created a Test Plan that sends a particular HTTP Request only once and sends another HTTP Request five times.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] We configured the Thread Group for a single thread and a loop count value of one.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Instead of letting the Thread Group control the looping, we used a Loop Controller.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] You can see that we added one HTTP Request to the Thread Group and another HTTP Request to a Loop Controller.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] We configured the Loop Controller with a loop count value of five.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] JMeter will send the requests in the following order: Home Page, News Page, News Page, News Page, News Page, and News Page.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Once Only Logic Controller tells JMeter to process the controller(s) inside it only once per Thread, and pass over any requests under it during further iterations through the test plan.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Once Only Controller will now execute always during the first iteration of any looping parent controller.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Thus, if the Once Only Controller is placed under a Loop Controller specified to loop 5 times, then the Once Only Controller will execute only on the first iteration through the Loop Controller (i.e. every 5 times).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Note this means the Once Only Controller will still behave as previously expected if put under a Thread Group (runs only once per test per Thread), but now the user has more flexibility in the use of the Once Only Controller.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] For testing that requires a login, consider placing the login request in this controller since each thread only needs to login once to establish a session.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] In this example, we created a Test Plan that has two threads that send HTTP request.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Each thread sends one request to the Home Page, followed by three requests to the Bug Page.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Although we configured the Thread Group to iterate three times, each JMeter thread only sends one request to the Home Page because this request lives inside a Once Only Controller.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Each JMeter thread will send the requests in the following order: Home Page, Bug Page, Bug Page, Bug Page.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Note, the File Reporter is configured to store the results in a file named "loop-test.dat" in the current directory.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If you add Generative or Logic Controllers to an Interleave Controller, JMeter will alternate among each of the other controllers for each loop iteration.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If checked, the interleave controller will treat sub-controllers like single request elements and only allow one request per controller at a time.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] In this example, we configured the Thread Group to have two threads and a loop count of five, for a total of ten requests per thread.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] See the table below for the sequence JMeter sends the HTTP Requests.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Download another example (see Figure 2).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] In this example, we configured the Thread Group to have a single thread and a loop count of eight.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Notice that the Test Plan has an outer Interleave Controller with two Interleave Controllers inside of it.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The outer Interleave Controller alternates between the two inner ones.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Then, each inner Interleave Controller alternates between each of the HTTP Requests.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Each JMeter thread will send the requests in the following order: Home Page, Interleaved, Bug Page, Interleaved, CVS Page, Interleaved, and FAQ Page, Interleaved.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Note, the File Reporter is configured to store the results in a file named "interleave-test2.dat" in the current directory.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If the two interleave controllers under the main interleave controller were instead simple controllers, then the order would be: Home Page, CVS Page, Interleaved, Bug Page, FAQ Page, Interleaved.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] However, if "ignore sub-controller blocks" was checked on the main interleave controller, then the order would be: Home Page, Interleaved, Bug Page, Interleaved, CVS Page, Interleaved, and FAQ Page, Interleaved.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Random Logic Controller acts similarly to the Interleave Controller, except that instead of going in order through its sub-controllers and samplers, it picks one at random at each pass.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Interactions between multiple controllers can yield complex behavior.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] This is particularly true of the Random Controller.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Random Order Controller is much like a Simple Controller in that it will execute each child element at most once, but the order of execution of the nodes will be random.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Throughput Controller allows the user to control how often it is executed.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] There are two modes: percent execution total executions Percent executions causes the controller to execute a certain percentage of the iterations through the test plan.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Total executions causes the controller to stop executing after a certain number of executions have occurred.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Like the Once Only Controller, this setting is reset when a parent Loop Controller restarts.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] This controller is badly named, as it does not control throughput.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] for an element that can be used to adjust the throughput.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Throughput Controller can yield very complex behavior when combined with other controllers - in particular with interleave or random controllers as parents (also very useful).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Whether the controller will run in percent executions or total executions mode.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] that indicates the percentage of times the controller will execute.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] " means the controller will execute during half the iterations through the test plan.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] For total execution mode, the number indicates the total number of times the controller will execute.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If checked, per user will cause the controller to calculate whether it should execute on a per user (per thread) basis.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If unchecked, then the calculation will be global for all users.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] ", then the number given for throughput will be the total number of executions made.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] " is checked, then the total number of executions would be the number of users times the number given for throughput.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Runtime Controller controls how long its children will run.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Controller will run its children until configured Runtime(s) is exceeded.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Descriptive name for this controller that is shown in the tree, and used to name the transaction.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The If Controller allows the user to control whether the test elements below it (its children) are run or not.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] By default, the condition is evaluated only once on initial entry, but you have the option to have it evaluated for every runnable element contained in the controller.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If the Variable Expression option is selected, then the expression is evaluated and compared with "true", without needing to use JavaScript.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] to test if a variable is defined and is not null.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Interpret Condition as Variable Expression?
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] will internally use javascript to evaluate the condition which has a performance penalty that can be very big and make your test less scalable.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Should condition be evaluated for all children?
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If not checked, then the condition is only evaluated on entry.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Note it is advised to avoid using JavaScript mode for performance.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] take care to not use variable replacement in the string, otherwise if using a variable that changes the script cannot be cached.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The While Controller runs its children until the condition is "false".
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] So for example, if your While Controller is named WC, then you can access the looping index through ${__jm__WC__idx}.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] function, properties or variables as needed.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Switch Controller acts like the Interleave Controller in that it runs one of the subordinate elements on each iteration, but rather than run them in sequence, the controller runs the element defined by the switch value.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If the switch value is out of range, it will run the zeroth element, which therefore acts as the default for the numeric case.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] It also runs the zeroth element if the value is the empty string.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If the value is non-numeric (and non-empty), then the Switch Controller looks for the element with the same name (case is significant).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If none of the names match, then the element named "default" (case not significant) is selected.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If there is no default, then no element is selected, and the controller will not run anything.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The number (or name) of the subordinate element to be invoked.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] A ForEach controller loops through the values of a set of related variables.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] When you add samplers (or controllers) to a ForEach controller, every sample (or controller) is executed one or more times, where during every loop the variable has a new value.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The input should consist of several variables, each extended with an underscore and a number.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Note: the "_" separator is now optional.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] When the return variable is given as "returnVar", the collection of samplers and controllers under the ForEach controller will be executed 4 consecutive times, with the return variable having the respective above values, which can then be used in the samplers.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] So for example, if your Loop Controller is named FEC, then you can access the looping index through ${__jm__FEC__idx}.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] It is especially suited for running with the regular expression post-processor.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] This can "create" the necessary input variables out of the result data of a previous request.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] By omitting the "_" separator, the ForEach Controller can be used to loop through the groups by using the input variable refName_g, and can also loop through all the groups in all the matches by using an input variable of the form refName_${C}_g, where C is a counter variable.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] This would be the case if the Regular Expression returned no matches.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Prefix for the variable names to be used as input.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The name of the variable which can be used in the loop for replacement in the samplers.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Defaults to an empty variable name, which is most probably not wanted.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] In this example, we created a Test Plan that sends a particular HTTP Request only once and sends another HTTP Request to every link that can be found on the page.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] You can see that we added one HTTP Request to the Thread Group and another HTTP Request to the ForEach Controller.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] In the ForEach loop, a HTTP sampler is added which requests all the links that were extracted from the first returned HTML page.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Here is another example you can download.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] This has two Regular Expressions and ForEach Controllers.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Thread Group has a single thread and a loop count of two.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Sample 1 uses the JavaTest Sampler to return the string "a b c d".
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Regex Extractor uses the expression (\w)\s which matches a letter followed by a space, and returns the letter (not the space).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Any matches are prefixed with the string "inputVar".
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The ForEach Controller extracts all variables with the prefix "inputVar_", and executes its sample, passing the value in the variable "returnVar".
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] In this case it will set the variable to the values "a" "b" and "c" in turn.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The For 1 Sampler is another Java Sampler which uses the return variable "returnVar" as part of the sample Label and as the sampler Data.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Sample 2, Regex 2 and For 2 are almost identical, except that the Regex has been changed to "(\w)\sx", which clearly won't match.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Module Controller provides a mechanism for substituting test plan fragments into the current test plan at run-time.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] A test plan fragment consists of a Controller and all the test elements (samplers etc.) contained in it.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The fragment can be located in any Thread Group.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If the fragment is located in a Thread Group, then its Controller can be disabled to prevent the fragment being run except by the Module Controller.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Or you can store the fragments in a dummy Thread Group, and disable the entire Thread Group.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] There can be multiple fragments, each with a different series of samplers under them.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The module controller can then be used to easily switch between these multiple test cases simply by choosing the appropriate controller in its drop down box.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] This provides convenience for running many alternate test plans quickly and easily.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] A fragment name is made up of the Controller name and all its parent names.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Any **fragments used by the Module Controller must have a unique name**, as the name is used to find the target controller when a test plan is reloaded.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] For this reason it is best to ensure that the Controller name is changed from the default - as shown in the example above - otherwise a duplicate may be accidentally created when new elements are added to the test plan.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The module controller provides a list of all controllers loaded into the gui.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Select the one you want to substitute in at runtime.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The include controller is designed to use an external JMX file.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] To use it, create a Test Fragment underneath the Test Plan and add any desired samplers, controllers etc. below it.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The file is now ready to be included as part of other Test Plans.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] For convenience, a Thread Group can also be added in the external JMX file for debugging purposes.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] A Module Controller can be used to reference the Test Fragment.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Thread Group will be ignored during the include process.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If the test uses a Cookie Manager or User Defined Variables, these should be placed in the top-level test plan, not the included file, otherwise they are not guaranteed to work.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] This element does not support variables/functions in the filename field.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] is defined, the contents are used to prefix the pathname.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If the file cannot be found at the location given by prefix+Filename, then the controller attempts to open the Filename relative to the JMX launch directory.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Transaction Controller generates an additional sample which measures the overall time taken to perform the nested test elements.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] " is checked, the time includes all processing within the controller scope, not just the samples.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The generated sample time includes all the times for the nested samplers excluding by default (since 2.11) timers and processing time of pre/post processors unless checkbox "Include duration of timer and pre-post processors in generated sample" is checked.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Depending on the clock resolution, it may be slightly longer than the sum of the individual samplers plus timers.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The clock might tick after the controller recorded the start time but before the first sample starts.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The generated sample is only regarded as successful if all its sub-samples are successful.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] In parent mode, the individual samples can still be seen in the Tree View Listener, but no longer appear as separate entries in other Listeners.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Also, the sub-samples do not appear in CSV log files, but they can be saved to XML files.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] In parent mode, Assertions (etc.) can be added to the Transaction Controller.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] However by default they will be applied to both the individual samples and the overall transaction sample.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] To limit the scope of the Assertions, use a Simple Controller to contain the samples, and add the Assertions to the Simple Controller.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Parent mode controllers do not currently properly support nested transaction controllers of either type.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If checked, then the sample is generated as a parent of the other samples, otherwise the sample is generated as an independent sample.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Whether to include timer, pre- and post-processing delays in the generated sample.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Recording Controller is a place holder indicating where the proxy server should record samples to.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] During test run, it has no effect, similar to the Simple Controller.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] But during recording using the HTTP(S) Test Script Recorder, all recorded samples will by default be saved under the Recording Controller.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Critical Section Controller ensures that its children elements (samplers/controllers, etc.) will be executed by only one thread as a named lock will be taken before executing children of controller.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Critical Section Controller takes locks only within one JVM, so if using Distributed testing ensure your use case does not rely on all threads of all JVMs blocking.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Most of the listeners perform several roles in addition to "listening" to the test results.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] They also provide means to view, save, and read saved test results.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Note that Listeners are processed at the end of the scope in which they are found.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The saving and reading of test results is generic.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The various listeners have a panel whereby one can specify the file to which the results will be written (or read from).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] By default, the results are stored as XML files, typically with a ".jtl" extension.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Storing as CSV is the most efficient option, but is less detailed than XML (the other available option).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] To read existing results and display them, use the file panel Browse button to open the file.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] If you want to clear any current data before loading a new file, use the menu item Run → Clear (Ctrl + Shift + E) or Run → Clear All (Ctrl + E) before loading the file.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Results can be read from XML or CSV format files.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] When reading from CSV results files, the header (if present) is used to determine which fields are present.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] **In order to interpret a header-less CSV file correctly, the appropriate properties must be set in jmeter.properties.** XML files written by JMeter have version 1.0 declared in header while actual file is serialized with 1.1 rules.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] (This is done for historical compatibility reasons; see Bug 59973 and Bug 58679) This causes strict XML parsers to fail.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Consider using non-strict XML parsers to read JTL files.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The file name can contain function and/or variable references.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] However variable references do not work in client-server mode (functions work OK).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] This is because the file is created on the client, and the client does not run the test locally so does not set up variables.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The following Listeners no longer need to keep copies of every single sample.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Instead, samples with the same elapsed time are aggregated.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Less memory is now needed, especially if most samples only take a second or two at most.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] To minimise the amount of memory needed, use the Simple Data Writer, and use the CSV format.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] JMeter variables can be saved to the output files.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] This can only be specified using a property.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] For full details on setting up the default items to be saved see the Listener Default Configuration documentation.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] For details of the contents of the output files, see the CSV log format or the XML log format.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] are used to define the defaults; these can be overridden for individual listeners by using the Configure button, as shown below.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Name of the file containing sample results.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The file name can be specified using either a relative or an absolute path name.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] JMeter also support paths relative to the directory containing the current test plan (JMX file).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] JMeter property), then the path is assumed to be relative to the JMX file location.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Select this to write/read only results without errors.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] is selected, then all results are processed.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Listeners can be configured to save different items to the result log files (JTL) by using the Config popup as shown below.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The defaults are defined as described in the Listener Default Configuration documentation.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Items with (CSV) after the name only apply to the CSV format; items with (XML) only apply to XML format.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] CSV format cannot currently be used to save any items that include line-breaks.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Note that cookies, method and the query string are saved as part of the "Sampler Data" option.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Graph Results MUST NOT BE USED during load test as it consumes a lot of resources (memory and CPU).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Use it only for either functional testing or during Test Plan debugging and Validation.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Graph Results listener generates a simple graph that plots all sample times.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Along the bottom of the graph, the current sample (black), the current average of all samples (blue), the current standard deviation (red), and the current throughput rate (green) are displayed in milliseconds.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The throughput number represents the actual number of requests/minute the server handled.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] This calculation includes any delays you added to your test and JMeter's own internal processing time.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The advantage of doing the calculation like this is that this number represents something real - your server in fact handled that many requests per minute, and you can increase the number of threads and/or decrease the delays to discover your server's maximum throughput.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Whereas if you made calculations that factored out delays and JMeter's processing, it would be unclear what you could conclude from that number.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The following table briefly describes the items on the graph.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Further details on the precise meaning of the statistical terms can be found on the web - e.g.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Wikipedia - or by consulting a book on statistics.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The individual figures at the bottom of the display are the current values.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] "Latest Sample" is the current elapsed sample time, shown on the graph as "Data".
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The value displayed on the top left of graph is the max of 90th percentile of response time.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] Assertion Results MUST NOT BE USED during load test as it consumes a lot of resources (memory and CPU).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] The Assertion Results visualizer shows the Label of each sample taken.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p03] It also reports failures of any Assertions that are part of the test plan.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] View Results Tree MUST NOT BE USED during load test as it consumes a lot of resources (memory and CPU).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The View Results Tree shows a tree of all sample responses, allowing you to view the response for any sample.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] In addition to showing the response, you can see the time it took to get this response, and some response codes.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Note that the Request panel only shows the headers added by JMeter.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] ) that may be added by the HTTP protocol implementation.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] There are several ways to view the response, selectable by a drop-down box at the bottom of the left hand panel.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Beware, that this might consume a lot of memory.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] With Search option, most of the views also allow the displayed data to be searched; the result of the search will be high-lighted in the display above.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] For example the Control panel screenshot below shows one result of searching for "Java".
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Note that the search operates on the visible text, so you may get different results when searching the Text and HTML views.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Note: The regular expression uses the Java engine (not ORO engine like the Regular Expression Extractor or Regexp Tester view).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If there is no content-type provided, then the content will not be displayed in the any of the Response Data panels.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] You can use Save Responses to a file to save the data in this case.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Note that the response data will still be available in the sample result, so can still be accessed using Post-Processors.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If the response data is larger than 200K, then it won't be displayed.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] To change this limit, set the JMeter property view.results.tree.max_size.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] You can also use save the entire response to a file using Save Responses to a file.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The class must implement the interface org.apache.jmeter.visualizers.ResultRenderer and/or extend the abstract class org.apache.jmeter.visualizers.SamplerResultTab, and the compiled code must be available to JMeter (e.g. by adding it to the lib/ext directory).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The Control Panel (above) shows an example of an HTML display.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Figure 9 (below) shows an example of an XML display.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Figure 9a (below) shows an example of a Regexp tester display.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Figure 9b (below) shows an example of a Document display.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The aggregate report creates a table row for each differently named request in your test.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] For each request, it totals the response information and provides request count, min, max, average, error rate, approximate throughput (request/second) and Kilobytes per second throughput.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Once the test is done, the throughput is the actual through for the duration of the entire test.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The throughput is calculated from the point of view of the sampler target (e.g. the remote server in the case of HTTP samples).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] JMeter takes into account the total time over which the requests have been generated.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If other samplers and timers are in the same thread, these will increase the total time, and therefore reduce the throughput value.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] So two identical samplers with different names will have half the throughput of two samplers with the same name.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] It is important to choose the sampler names correctly to get the best results from the Aggregate Report.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Calculation of the Median and 90 % Line (90th percentile) values requires additional memory.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] JMeter now combines samples with the same elapsed time, so far less memory is used.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] However, for samples that take more than a few seconds, the probability is that fewer samples will have identical times, in which case more memory will be needed.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Note you can use this listener afterwards to reload a CSV or XML results file which is the recommended way to avoid performance impacts.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] See the Summary Report for a similar Listener that does not store individual samples and so needs constant memory.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The figure below shows an example of selecting the "Include group name" checkbox.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] This visualizer creates a row for every sample result.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] By default, it only displays the main (parent) samples; it does not display the sub-samples (child samples).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] JMeter has a "Child Samples?" check-box.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If this is selected, then the sub-samples are displayed instead of the main samples.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] This listener can record results to a file but not to the UI.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] It is meant to provide an efficient means of recording data by eliminating GUI overhead.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The fields to save are defined by JMeter properties.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The aggregate graph is similar to the aggregate report.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The primary difference is the aggregate graph provides an easy way to generate bar graphs and save the graph as a PNG file.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The figure below shows an example of settings to draw this graph.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Define the graph's title on the head of chart.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] define the title with the label of the listener.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Compute the graph size by the width and height depending of the current JMeter's window size.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Define the max length of X Axis label (in pixel).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Define a custom maximum value for Y Axis.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The Response Time Graph draws a line chart showing the evolution of response time during the test, for each labelled request.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If many samples exist for the same timestamp, the mean value is displayed.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The time in milliseconds for X axis interval.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Samples are grouped according to this value.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Customize the date format of X axis label.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Define a custom maximum value for Y Axis in milli-seconds.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Define the increment for the scale (in ms) Show or not the number grouping in Y Axis labels.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The mailer visualizer can be set up to send email if a test run receives too many failed responses from the server.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Email address to send messages to, comma-separated.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Email subject line for success messages.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The mailer will thus only send out messages in a sequence of failed-succeeded-failed-succeeded, etc.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] IP address or host name of SMTP server (email redirector) server.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Type of encryption for SMTP authentication (SSL, TLS or none).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] A field that keeps a running total of number of failures so far received.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The BeanShell Listener allows the use of BeanShell for processing samples for saving etc.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The test element supports the ThreadListener and TestListener methods.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] These should be defined in the initialisation file.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If the property beanshell.listener.init is defined, this is used to load an initialisation file, which can be used to define methods etc. for use in the BeanShell script.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The summary report creates a table row for each differently named request in your test.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] It is important to choose the sampler labels correctly to get the best results from the Report.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] This test element can be placed anywhere in the test plan.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] For each sample in its scope, it will create a file of the response Data.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The primary use for this is in creating functional tests, but it can also be useful where the response is too large to be displayed in the View Results Tree Listener.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The file name is created from the specified prefix, plus a number (unless this is disabled, see below).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The file extension is created from the document type, if known.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If not known, the file extension is set to 'unknown'.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If numbering is disabled, and adding a suffix is disabled, then the file prefix is taken as the entire file name.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] This allows a fixed file name to be generated if required.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The generated file name is stored in the sample response, and can be saved in the test log output file if required.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The current sample is saved first, followed by any sub-samples (child samples).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If a variable name is provided, then the names of the files are saved in the order that the sub-samples appear.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Prefix for the generated file names; this can include a directory name.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] JMeter also supports paths relative to the directory containing the current test plan (JMX file).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If parent folders in prefix do not exists, JMeter will create them and stop test if it fails.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Name of a variable in which to save the generated file name (so it can be used later in the test plan).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If there are sub-samples then a numeric suffix is added to the variable name.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] so that prefix is has size of this value.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If selected, then no number is added to the prefix.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If you select this option, make sure that the prefix is unique or the file may be overwritten.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The JSR223 Listener allows JSR223 script code to be applied to sample results.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] interface (Groovy is one of these, java, beanshell and javascript are not).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Generates a summary of the test run so far to the log file and/or standard output.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Both running and differential totals are shown.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] seconds (default 30 seconds) on the appropriate time boundary, so that multiple test runs on the same time will be synchronised.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] This element is mainly intended for batch (CLI) runs.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] means that the line is a delta line, i.e. shows the changes since the last output.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] means that the line is a total line, i.e. it shows the running total.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Entries in the JMeter log file also include time-stamps.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] " means that there were 817 samples recorded in 5 minutes and 7 seconds, and that works out at 2.7 samples per second.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] " means number of errors (also shown as percentage).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The last two lines will appear at the end of a test.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] They will not be synchronised to the appropriate time boundary.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Note that the initial and final deltas may be for less than the interval (in the example above this is 30 seconds).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The first delta will generally be lower, as JMeter synchronizes to the interval boundary.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The last delta will be lower, as the test will generally not finish on an exact interval boundary.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The label is used to group sample results together.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] So if you have multiple Thread Groups and want to summarize across them all, then use the same label - or add the summariser to the Test Plan (so all thread groups are in scope).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Different summary groupings can be implemented by using suitable labels and adding the summarisers to appropriate parts of the test plan.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] " is configured, if you have already added one to your Test Plan, ensure you name it differently otherwise results will be accumulated under this label (summary) leading to wrong results (sum of total samples + samples located under the Parent of Generate Summary Results listener).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] This is not a bug but a design choice allowing to summarize across thread groups.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Details for all elements with the same label will be added together.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] By default, a Graphite implementation is provided.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Size of the queue that holds the SampleResults while they are processed asynchronously.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] ." Note that JMeter does not add a separator between the root prefix and the samplerName which is why the trailing dot is currently needed.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Defines the names (labels) of sample results to be sent to the back end.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] this is a list of semi-colon separated names.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] this is a regular expression which will be matched against the names.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Consider samplersList as a regular expression to select the samplers for which you want to report metrics to backend.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The percentiles you want to send to the backend.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] (The separator is always ".") List must be semicolon separated.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Generally 3 or 4 values should be sufficient.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] See also Real-time results for more details.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Since JMeter 3.2, an implementation that allows writing directly in InfluxDB with a custom schema.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] It is called InfluxdbBackendListenerClient.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Regular expression which will be matched against the names of samples and sent to the back end.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Grafana allow to display tag for each annotation.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Generally three or four values should be sufficient.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] You can add as many custom tags as you want.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] See also Real-time results and Influxdb annotations in Grafana for more details.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] There is also a subsection on configuring the listener for InfluxDB v2.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Since JMeter 5.4, an implementation that writes all sample results to InfluxDB.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] It is called InfluxDBRawBackendListenerClient.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] It is worth noting that this will use more resources than the InfluxdbBackendListenerClient, both by JMeter and InfluxDB due to the increase in data and individual writes.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Configuration elements can be used to set up defaults and variables for later use by samplers.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Note that these elements are processed at the start of the scope in which they are found, i.e. before any samplers in the same scope.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] CSV Data Set Config is used to read lines from a file, and split them into variables.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] It is easier to use than the __CSVRead() and __StringFromFile() functions.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] It is well suited to handling large numbers of variables, and is also useful for testing with "random" and unique values.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Generating unique random values at run-time is expensive in terms of CPU and memory, so just create the data in advance of the test.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If necessary, the "random" data from the file can be used in conjunction with a run-time parameter to create different sets of values from each run - e.g. using concatenation - which is much cheaper than generating everything at run-time.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] JMeter allows values to be quoted; this allows the value to contain a delimiter.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If "allow quoted data" is enabled, a value may be enclosed in double-quotes.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] To include double-quotes within a quoted field, use two double-quotes.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] JMeter supports CSV files which have a header line defining the column names.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] To enable this, leave the "Variable Names" field empty.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] JMeter supports CSV files with quoted data that includes new-lines.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] By default, the file is only opened once, and each thread will use a different line from the file.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] However the order in which lines are passed to threads depends on the order in which they execute, which may vary between iterations.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Lines are read at the start of each test iteration.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The file name and mode are resolved in the first iteration.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] See the description of the Share mode below for additional options.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If you want each thread to have its own set of values, then you will need to create a set of files, one for each thread.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] For example test1.csv, test2.csv, …, test*n*.csv.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Use the filename test${__threadNum}.csv and set the "Sharing mode" to "Current thread".
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] CSV Dataset variables are defined at the start of each test iteration.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] As a special case, the string "\t" (without quotes) in the delimiter field is treated as a Tab.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] When the end of file (EOF) is reached, and the recycle option is true, reading starts again with the first line of the file.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If the recycle option is false, and stopThread is false, then all the variables are set to <EOF> when the end of file is reached.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] This value can be changed by setting the JMeter property csvdataset.eofstring.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If the Recycle option is false, and Stop Thread is true, then reaching EOF will cause the thread to be stopped.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Relative file names are resolved with respect to the path of the active test plan.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] For distributed testing, the CSV file must be stored on the server host system in the correct relative directory to where the JMeter server is started.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Absolute file names are also supported, but note that they are unlikely to work in remote mode, unless the remote server has the same directory structure.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If the same physical file is referenced in two different ways - e.g.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The encoding to be used to read the file, if not the platform default.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The names must be separated by the delimiter character.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] JMeter supports CSV header lines: if the variable name field empty, then the first line of the file is read and interpreted as the list of column names.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Ignore first line of CSV file, it will only be used if Variable Names is not empty, if Variable Names is empty the first line must contain the headers.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Delimiter to be used to split the records in the file.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If there are fewer values on the line than there are variables the remaining variables are not updated - so they will retain their previous value (if any).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Should the CSV file allow values to be quoted?
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The DNS Cache Manager element allows to test applications, which have several servers behind load balancers (CDN, etc.), when user receives content from different IP's.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] That's why only one server from the cluster receives load.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] DNS Cache Manager resolves names for each thread separately each iteration and saves results of resolving to its internal DNS Cache, which is independent from both JVM and OS DNS caches.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] A mapping for static hosts can be used to simulate something like /etc/hosts file.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] These entries will be preferred over the custom resolver.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Use custom DNS resolver has to be enabled, if you want to use this mapping.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Say, you have a test server, that you want to reach with a name, that is not (yet) set up in your DNS servers.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] For our example, this would be www.example.com for the server name, which you want to reach at the IP of the server a123.another.example.org.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] You could change your workstation and add an entry to your /etc/hosts file - or the equivalent for your OS, or add an entry to the Static Host Table of the DNS Cache Manager.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] You would type www.example.com into the first column (Host) and a123.another.example.org into the second column (Hostname or IP address).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] As the name of the second column implies, you could even use the IP address of your test server there.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] The IP address for the test server will be looked up by using the custom DNS resolver.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] When none is given, the system DNS resolver will be used.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Now you can use www.example.com in your HTTPClient4 samplers and the requests will be made against a123.another.example.org with all headers set to www.example.com.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] DNS Cache Manager is designed for using in the root of Thread Group or Test Plan.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] DNS Cache Manager works only with HTTP requests using HTTPClient4 implementation.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If selected, DNS cache of every Thread is cleared each time new iteration is started.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Custom DNS resolver (from dnsjava library) will be used.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] If empty, network configuration DNS will used.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Delete the currently selected table entry.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Mapping of hostnames to a static host entry which will be resolved using the custom DNS resolver.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p04] Delete the currently selected static host in the table.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The Authorization Manager lets you specify one or more user logins for web pages that are restricted using server authentication.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] You see this type of authentication when you use your browser to access a restricted page, and your browser displays a login dialog box.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] JMeter transmits the login information when it encounters this type of page.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The Authorization headers may not be shown in the Tree View Listener "Request" tab.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The Java implementation does pre-emptive authentication, but it does not return the Authorization header when JMeter fetches the headers.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The HttpComponents (HC 4.5.X) implementation defaults to pre-emptive since 3.2 and the header will be shown.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] To disable this, set the values as below, in which case authentication will only be performed in response to a challenge.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Note: the above settings only apply to the HttpClient sampler.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] When looking for a match against a URL, JMeter checks each entry in turn, and stops when it finds the first match.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Thus the most specific URLs should appear first in the list, followed by less specific ones.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If you want to use different usernames/passwords for different threads, you can use variables.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If there is more than one Authorization Manager in the scope of a Sampler, there is currently no way to specify which one is to be used.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If checked, authentication will be done on each iteration of Main Thread Group loop even if it has already been done in a previous one.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] This is usually useful if each main thread group iteration represents behaviour of one Virtual User.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] A partial or complete URL that matches one or more HTTP Request URLs.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The Realm only applies to the HttpClient sampler.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] You can also configure those two properties in the file bin/system.properties.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Look at the two sample configuration files (krb5.conf and jaas.conf) located in the JMeter bin folder for references to more documentation, and tweak them to match your Kerberos configuration.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Delegation of credentials is disabled by default for SPNEGO.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If you want to enable it, you can do so by setting the property kerberos.spnego.delegate_cred to true.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] When generating a SPN for Kerberos SPNEGO authentication IE and Firefox will omit the port number from the URL.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Chrome has an option (--enable-auth-negotiate-port) to include the port number if it differs from the standard ones (80 and 443).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] That behavior can be emulated by setting the following JMeter property as below.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] When you save the Test Plan, JMeter automatically saves all of the authorization table entries - including any passwords, which are not encrypted.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] In this example, we created a Test Plan on a local server that sends three HTTP requests, two requiring a login and the other is open to everyone.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] See figure 10 to see the makeup of our Test Plan.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] On our server, we have a restricted directory named, "secret", which contains two files, "index.html" and "index2.html".
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] We created a login id named, "kevin", which has a password of "spot".
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] So, in our Authorization Manager, we created an entry for the restricted directory and a username and password (see figure 11).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The two HTTP requests named "SecretPage1" and "SecretPage2" make requests to "/secret/index.html" and "/secret/index2.html".
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The other HTTP request, named "NoSecretPage" makes a request to "/index.html".
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] When we run the Test Plan, JMeter looks in the Authorization table for the URL it is requesting.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If the Base URL matches the URL, then JMeter passes this information along with the request.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] You can download the Test Plan, but since it is built as a test for our local server, you will not be able to run it.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] However, you can use it as a reference in constructing your own Test Plan.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The HTTP Cache Manager is used to add caching functionality to HTTP requests within its scope to simulate browser cache feature.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Each Virtual User thread has its own Cache.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] By default, Cache Manager will store up to 5000 items in cache per Virtual User thread, using LRU algorithm.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Use property "maxSize" to modify this value.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Note that the more you increase this value the more HTTP Cache Manager will consume memory, so be sure to adapt the -Xmx JVM option accordingly.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If a sample is successful (i.e. has response code 2xx) then the Last-Modified and Etag (and Expired if relevant) values are saved for the URL.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Before executing the next sample, the sampler checks to see if there is an entry in the cache, and if so, the If-Last-Modified and If-None-Match conditional headers are set for the request.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Additionally, if the "Use Cache-Control/Expires header" option is selected, then the Cache-Control/Expires value is checked against the current time.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If the request is a GET request, and the timestamp is in the future, then the sampler returns immediately, without requesting the URL from the remote server.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] This is intended to emulate browser behaviour.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Note that if Cache-Control header is "no-cache", the response will be stored in cache as pre-expired, so will generate a conditional GET request.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If Cache-Control has any other value, the "max-age" expiry option is processed to compute entry lifetime, if missing then expire header will be used, if also missing entry will be cached as specified in RFC 2616 section 13.2.4 using Last-Modified time and response Date.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If the requested document has not changed since it was cached, then the response body will be empty.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If selected, then the cache is cleared at the start of the thread.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The Cookie Manager element has two functions: First, it stores and sends cookies just like a web browser.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If you have an HTTP Request and the response contains a cookie, the Cookie Manager automatically stores that cookie and will use it for all future requests to that particular web site.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Each JMeter thread has its own "cookie storage area".
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] So, if you are testing a web site that uses a cookie for storing session information, each JMeter thread will have its own session.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Note that such cookies do not appear on the Cookie Manager display, but they can be seen using the View Results Tree Listener.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] JMeter checks that received cookies are valid for the URL.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] This means that cross-domain cookies are not stored.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If you have bugged behaviour or want Cross-Domain cookies to be used, define the JMeter property "CookieManager.check.cookies=false".
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Received Cookies can be stored as JMeter thread variables.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] To save cookies as variables, define the property "CookieManager.save.cookies=true".
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Also, cookies names are prefixed with "COOKIE_" before they are stored (this avoids accidental corruption of local variables) To revert to the original behaviour, define the property "CookieManager.name.prefix= " (one or more spaces).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If enabled, the value of a cookie with the name TEST can be referred to as ${COOKIE_TEST}.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Second, you can manually add a cookie to the Cookie Manager.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] However, if you do this, the cookie will be shared by all JMeter threads.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Cookies with null values are ignored by default.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] This can be changed by setting the JMeter property: CookieManager.delete_null_cookies=false.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Note that this also applies to manually defined cookies - any such cookies will be removed from the display when it is updated.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Note also that the cookie name must be unique - if a second cookie is defined with the same name, it will replace the first.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If there is more than one Cookie Manager in the scope of a Sampler, there is currently no way to specify which one is to be used.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Also, a cookie stored in one cookie manager is not available to any other manager, so use multiple Cookie Managers with care.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If selected, all server-defined cookies are cleared each time the main Thread Group loop is executed.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Any cookie defined in the GUI are not cleared.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The cookie policy that will be used to manage the cookies.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] " is the default since 3.0, and should work in most cases.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] This gives you the opportunity to use hardcoded cookies that will be used by all threads during the test execution.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Load a previously saved cookie table and add the entries to the existing cookie table entries.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Save the current cookie table to a file (does not save any cookies extracted from HTTP Responses).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] This element lets you set default values that your HTTP Request controllers use.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] For example, if you are creating a Test Plan with 25 HTTP Request controllers and all of the requests are being sent to the same server, you could add a single HTTP Request Defaults element with the "Server Name or IP" field filled in.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Then, when you add the 25 HTTP Request controllers, leave the "Server Name or IP" field empty.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The controllers will inherit this field value from the HTTP Request Defaults element.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] All port values are treated equally; a sampler that does not specify a port will use the HTTP Request Defaults port, if one is provided.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The encoding to be used for the request.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Note that the path is the default for the full path, not a prefix to be applied to paths specified on the HTTP Request screens.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Note: radio buttons only have two states - on or off.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] This makes it impossible to override settings consistently - does off mean off, or does it mean use the current default?
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] JMeter uses the latter (otherwise defaults would not work at all).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] So if the button is off, then a later element can set it on, but if the button is on, a later element cannot set it off.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The Header Manager lets you add or override HTTP request headers.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Load a previously saved header table and add the entries to the existing header table entries.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Save the current header table to a file.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] In this example, we created a Test Plan that tells JMeter to override the default "User-Agent" request header and use a particular Internet Explorer agent string instead.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The Java Request Defaults component lets you set default values for Java testing.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Sampler) from the supplied JDBC Connection settings.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The connection may be optionally pooled between threads.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Otherwise each thread gets its own connection.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The connection configuration name is used by the JDBC Sampler to select the appropriate connection.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Descriptive name for the connection configuration that is shown in the tree.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The name of the variable the connection is tied to.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Multiple connections can be used, each tied to a different variable, allowing JDBC Samplers to select the appropriate connection.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If there are two configuration elements using the same name, only one will be saved.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] JMeter logs a message if a duplicate name is detected.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Maximum number of connections allowed in the pool.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] This means that each thread will get its own pool with a single connection in it, i.e. the connections are not shared between threads.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If you really want to use shared pooling (why?), then set the max count to the same as the number of threads to ensure threads don't wait on each other.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The number of milliseconds to sleep between runs of the idle object evictor thread.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] When non-positive, no idle object evictor thread will be run.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Turn auto commit on or off for the connections.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Max number of Prepared Statements to pool per connection.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] " means unlimited number of Prepared Statements to pool.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The connection pool can be initialized instantly.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] (default), the JDBC request samplers using this pool might measure higher response times for the first queries – as the connection establishment time for the whole pool is included.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] A Collection of SQL statements that will be used to initialize physical connections when they are first created.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] These statements are executed only once - when the configured connection factory creates the connection.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Validation Query will be used to test it.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] A simple query used to determine if the database is still responding.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] ' method of the jdbc driver, which is suitable for many databases.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] " suggests query would only be used on idle connections.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] JDBC Connection string for the database.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Different databases and JDBC drivers require different JDBC settings.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The Database URL and JDBC Driver class are defined by the provider of the JDBC implementation.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Please check the exact details in the JDBC driver documentation.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If the database server is not running or is not accessible, then JMeter will report a java.net.ConnectException.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Some examples for databases and their parameters are given below.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The above may not be correct - please check the relevant JDBC driver documentation.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The Keystore Config Element lets you configure how Keystore will be loaded and which keys it will use.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] This component is typically used in HTTPS scenarios where you don't want to take into account keystore initialization into account in response time.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] To use PKCS11 as the source for the store, you need to set javax.net.ssl.keyStoreType to PKCS11 and javax.net.ssl.keyStore to NONE.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Variable name that will contain the alias to use for authentication by client certificate.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Variable value will be filled from CSV Data Set for example.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] " will also be a variable in CSV Data Set.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The index of the first key to use in Keystore, 0-based.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The index of the last key to use in Keystore, 0-based.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] " ensure it is large enough so that all keys are loaded at startup.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The Login Config Element lets you add or override username and password settings in samplers that use username and password as part of their setup.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The LDAP Request Defaults component lets you set default values for LDAP testing.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The LDAP Extended Request Defaults component lets you set default values for extended LDAP testing.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Connect Timeout (milliseconds, 0 disables).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Response Timeout (milliseconds, 0 disables).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The User Defined Variables element lets you define an **initial set of variables**, just as in the Test Plan.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Note that all the UDV elements in a test plan - no matter where they are - are processed at the start.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] So you cannot reference variables which are defined as part of a test run, e.g. in a Post-Processor.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] which would define the variable "HOST" to have the value of the JMeter property "host", defaulting to "localhost" if not defined.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] For defining variables during a test run, see User Parameters.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] UDVs are processed in the order they appear in the Plan, from top to bottom.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] For simplicity, it is suggested that UDVs are placed only at the start of a Thread Group (or perhaps under the Test Plan itself).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Once the Test Plan and all UDVs have been processed, the resulting set of variables is copied to each thread to provide the initial set of variables.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If a runtime element such as a User Parameters Pre-Processor or Regular Expression Extractor defines a variable with the same name as one of the UDV variables, then this will replace the initial value, and all other test elements in the thread will see the updated value.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If you have more than one Thread Group, make sure you use different names for different values, as UDVs are shared between Thread Groups.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Also, the variables are not available for use until after the element has been processed, so you cannot reference variables that are defined in the same element.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] You can reference variables defined in earlier UDVs or on the Test Plan.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] constructs to use the variables later on.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The Random Variable Config Element is used to generate random numeric strings and store them in variable for use later.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] It's simpler than using User Defined Variables together with the __Random() function.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The output variable is constructed by using the random number generator, and then the resulting number is formatted using the format string.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The number is calculated using the formula minimum+Random.nextInt(maximum-minimum+1).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Random.nextInt() requires a positive integer.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] This means that maximum-minimum - i.e. the range - must be less than 2147483647, however the minimum and maximum values can be any long values so long as the range is OK.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] As the random value is evaluated at the start of each iteration, it is probably not a good idea to use a variable other than a property as a value for the minimum or maximum.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] It would be zero on the first iteration.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The name of the variable in which to store the random string.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The seed for the random number generator.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If no seed is set, Default constructor of Random will be used.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] , the generator is shared between all threads in the thread group.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] , then each thread has its own random generator.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Allows the user to create a counter that can be referenced anywhere in the Thread Group.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The counter config lets the user configure a starting point, a maximum, and the increment.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The counter will loop from the start to the max, and then start over with the start, continuing on like that until the test is ended.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The counter uses a long to store the value, so the range is from -2^63 to 2^63-1.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The counter will equal this value during the first iteration (defaults to 0).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] How much to increment the counter by after each iteration (defaults to 0, meaning no increment).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] This will be the variable name under which the counter value is available.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] In other words, is this a global counter, or does each user get their own counter?
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If checked, each user has an independent counter.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] This can be useful when Counter is inside a Loop Controller.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The Simple Config Element lets you add or override arbitrary values in samplers.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] You can choose the name of the value and the value itself.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Although some adventurous users might find a use for this element, it's here primarily for developers as a basic GUI that they can use while developing new JMeter components.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] These values are internal to JMeter's workings and are not generally documented.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Only those familiar with the code will know these values.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Sampler) from the supplied Connection settings.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] , the driver will keep trying to connect to the same server in case that the socket cannot be established.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] There is maximum amount of time to keep retrying, which is 15s by default.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] This can be useful to avoid some exceptions being thrown when a server is down temporarily by blocking the operations.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] It can also be useful to smooth the transition to a new primary node (so that a new primary node is elected within the retry time).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Even if this flag is false, the driver already has mechanisms to automatically recreate broken connections and retry the read operations.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The maximum amount of time in milliseconds to spend retrying to open connection to the same server.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The maximum wait time in milliseconds that a thread may wait for a connection to become available.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] This multiplier, multiplied with the connectionsPerHost setting, gives the maximum number of threads that may be waiting for a connection to become available from the pool.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] All further threads will get an exception right away.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] , then up to 50 threads can wait for a connection.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Max size of the Neo4j driver Bolt connection pool.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Raise the value if running large number of concurrent threads, so that JMeter threads are not blocked waiting for a connection to be released to the pool.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Assertions are used to perform additional checks on samplers, and are processed after **every sampler** in the same scope.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] To ensure that an Assertion is applied only to a particular sampler, add it as a child of the sampler.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Note: Unless documented otherwise, Assertions are not applied to sub-samples (child samples) - only to the parent sample.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] which returns an array of SampleResults.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The array will be empty if there are none.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Assertions can be applied to either the main sample, the sub-samples or both.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The default is to apply the assertion to the main sample only.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If a sub-sampler fails and the main sample is successful, then the main sample will be set to failed status and an Assertion Result will be added.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If the JMeter variable option is used, it is assumed to relate to the main sample, and any failure will be applied to the main sample only.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] " after all assertions for a sampler have been run.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The response assertion control panel lets you add pattern strings to be compared against various fields of the request or response.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] A summary of the pattern matching characters can be found at ORO Perl5 regular expressions.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] You can also choose whether the strings will be expected to **match** the entire response, or if the response is only expected to **contain** the pattern.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] You can attach multiple assertions to any controller for additional flexibility.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Note that the pattern string should not include the enclosing delimiters, i.e. use Price: \d+ not /Price: \d+/.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] By default, the pattern is in multi-line mode, which means that the "." meta-character does not match newline.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] In multi-line mode, "^" and "$" match the start or end of any line anywhere within the string - not just the start and end of the entire string.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] To override these settings, one can use the *extended regular expression* syntax.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] These can be used anywhere within the expression and remain in effect until overridden.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] This is for use with samplers that can generate sub-samples, e.g.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] HTTP Sampler with embedded resources, Mail Reader or samples generated by the Transaction Controller.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Instructs JMeter which field of the Request or Response to test.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Instructs JMeter to set the status to success initially.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The overall success of the sample is determined by combining the result of the assertion with the existing Response status.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] When the Ignore Status checkbox is selected, the Response status is forced to successful before evaluating the Assertion.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] ranges are normally regarded as unsuccessful.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] " checkbox can be used to set the status successful before performing further checks.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Note that this will have the effect of clearing any previous assertion failures, so make sure that this is only set on the first assertion.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Indicates how the text being tested is checked against the pattern.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] patterns are plain strings, not regular expressions.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] may also be selected to invert the result of the check.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Apply each assertion in OR combination (if 1 pattern to test matches, Assertion will be ok) instead of AND (All patterns must match so that Assertion is OK).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] If a pattern fails, then further patterns are not checked.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] There is no difference between setting up one Assertion with multiple patterns and setting up multiple Assertions with one pattern each (assuming the other options are the same).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] checkbox is only used on the first Assertion.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The pattern is a Perl5-style regular expression, but without the enclosing brackets.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The Duration Assertion tests that each response was received within a given amount of time.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] Any response that takes longer than the given number of milliseconds (specified by the user) is marked as a failed response.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p05] The maximum number of milliseconds each response is allowed before being marked as failed.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p06] The Size Assertion tests that each response contains the right number of bytes in it.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p06] You can specify that the size be equal to, greater than, less than, or not equal to a given number of bytes.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p06] An empty response is treated as being 0 bytes rather than reported as an error.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p06] The number of bytes to use in testing the size of the response (or value of the JMeter variable).
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p06] Whether to test that the response is equal to, greater than, less than, or not equal to, the number of bytes specified.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p06] The XML Assertion tests that the response data consists of a formally correct XML document.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p06] It does not validate the XML based on a DTD or schema or do any further validation.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p06] The BeanShell Assertion allows the user to perform assertion checking using a BeanShell script.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p06] Note that a different Interpreter is used for each independent occurrence of the assertion in each thread in a test script, but the same Interpreter is used for subsequent invocations.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p06] This means that variables persist across calls to the assertion.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p06] All Assertions are called from the same thread as the sampler.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p06] If the property "beanshell.assertion.init" is defined, it is passed to the Interpreter as the name of a sourced file.
[src:jmeter/component-reference-p06] Before invoking the script, some variables are set up in the BeanShell interpreter.
